C. Niek van Dijk, Ph.D., and Nanne Kort, M.D.
Summary: An anatomic cadaver study was performed.
Subsequently, in a prospective study, diagnostic and therapeutic tendoscopy (tendon sheath endoscopy) was performed in nine consecutive patients with a history of persistent posterolateral ankle pain for at least 6 months.
All patients had pain on palpation over the peroneal tendons, a positive peroneal tendon resistance test, and most often local swelling.
In two patients, a peroneal click was found without symptoms of dislocation of the tendons over the ﬁbula.
The indications for arthroscopy were diagnostic procedure postsurgery (3), diagnostic procedure postfracture (2), snapping sensation (2), removal of exostosis (1), and partial tendon rupture (1).
Inspection and surgery of both tendons and tendon sheath could be performed well by a standard two-portal technique.
A new ﬁnding is the vincula that was consistently present in all our autopsy specimens, as well as in all our patients.
The vincula attaches both tendons to each other and to the tendon sheath.
At a mean follow-up of 19 months, three of the four patients in which adhesions were found and resected were symptom free.
In one patient, a symptomatic prominent peroneal tubercle was successfully removed.
One patient had a longitudinal rupture of the peroneus brevis tendon that was successfully sutured.
There were no complications.
Key Words: Tendoscopy—Peroneal tendon—Tendon rupture—Tendinopathy—Tendon sheath—Endoscopy.

C. Niek van Dijk, Ph.D., and Nanne Kort, M.D.
 | Complaints around the ankle joint can be derived from intra-articular and extra-articular pathology. During the last decades, the arthroscope has become a major tool to diagnose and particularly treat intra- articular ankle lesions like impingement syndromes, synovitis, osteochondral defects, loose bodies and arthrosis.1-5 In the absence of intra-articular pathology, postero- lateral ankle complaints most often are caused by disorders of the peroneal tendons. In the event of failure of conservative treatment, disorders like tenosy- novitis, partial tendon rupture, hypertrophic tendinopa- thy and a prominent peroneal tubercle can be treated by open surgery. | Postoperative open surgical treatment requires plas- ter immobilisation to prevent equinus malformation and to stimulate wound healing.6,7 A possible endo- scopic procedure would offer several advantages such as less morbidity, reduction in postoperative pain, functional after-treatment, and outpatient treatment.8 A cadaver study was performed and, subsequently, in a prospective study diagnostic and therapeutic tendos- copy (tendon sheath endoscopy) was performed in nine consecutive patients.
 | ANATOMIC STUDY
 | Seven ankles in ﬁve specimens with no previous history of ankle pathology were dissected. Special attention was paid to the relation of the peroneal tendons to each other, to the posterolateral aspect of the distal ﬁbula and to the lateral bony aspects of the calcaneus and cuboid.

This thin vincula-like structure runs between the peroneus longus and the peroneus brevis tendon and is dorsally attached to the dorsolateral aspect of the ﬁbula.
When stretched out it provides an intertendinous distance of 3 to 4 cm (Fig 2).
The distal ﬁbers of the peroneal brevis muscle belly gradually transform to this membranous layer to end approximately at the tip of the ﬁbula.
This vincula-like structure runs all the way down to the distal insertion of the tendons.
Proximal to the lateral malleolus, the peroneus brevis tendon has a ﬂat contour.
Just distal to the tip of the lateral malleolus, the tendon becomes round and crosses round the peroneus longus tendon.
The posterolateral part of the ﬁbula constitutes a sliding channel for the two peroneal tendons.
In 3 of the 7 explorations, the bony prominence on the calcaneus was found in between both tendons, some 4 to 5 cm distal from the tip of the ﬁbula.

SURGICAL TECHNIQUE
An autopsy study was performed to verify portal anatomy.
Access to the tendon can be obtained anywhere along its course.
However, the two main portals are located directly over the tendons 1.5 to 2 cm distal and 2 to 2.5 cm proximal of the posterior edge of the lateral malleolus (Fig 3).
The distal portal is made ﬁrst: the incision is made through the skin only and the tendon sheath is penetrated by the sleeve with a blunt trocard.
The 2.7-mm arthroscope with an inclination angle of 30° is introduced and the tendon sheath is ﬁlled with saline.
The 1-mm needle scope and the 1.8-mm arthroscope were used at ﬁrst but were found to give inferior access and view.
Another important advantage of the 2.7-mm arthroscope is the far better ﬂow which is necessary when surgery is undertaken.
Under direct vision, the proximal portal is made by introduction of a spinal needle and subsequently an incision is made through the skin into the tendon sheath.
Instruments like a blunt probe, scissors, retrograde knife, and shaver system can be introduced.
The distal portal allows a complete overview over both tendons from 6 cm above the level of the posterior tip of the lateral malleolus (Fig 4).
Distally, at the level of the peroneal tubercle, both tendons separate and get surrounded by their own tendon sheath (Fig 5).
Both tendons and tendon sheath can be inspected by rotating the scope around the tendons.
The operation is performed as an outpatient procedure under general, regional, or local anesthesia.
Local anesthesia has the advantage of a possible dynamic investigation.
Before the anesthesia is administered, the patient is asked to actively evert the foot.
The peroneal tendons thus can be palpated and the location of the portals can be drawn on the skin.
In case of local anesthesia, the anesthetic (plus adrenaline) is administered at the portal site and into the tendon sheath.
In case of a tendon sheath release, we use a small retrograde knife.
Under direct vision, a release of the complete tendon sheath can be performed from 6 cm above the joint level up to the level of the peroneal tubercle.
At the end of the procedure the portals are sutured.
Postoperative treatment consists of a pressure bandage and partial weight bearing for 2 to 3 days.
Active movements are stimulated from day 1.

INDICATIONS
Peroneal tenosynovitis is associated with chronic mechanical irritation, ankle trauma (sprain or calcaneal fracture), or foot deformities.9,10-12 On physical examination there is tenderness on palpation, edema, and increase of symptoms on active eversion against resistance.10,12-14 Peroneal tenography is reported to be useful to detect stenosing tenosynovitis.14,15 Most authors report good results with conservative treatment: rest, physical therapy, orthosis, and inﬁltration.10,12 Zivot and Pearl14 reported on three patients with a positive tenography in which conservative treatment failed.

There were six women and three men.
The average age was 34.4 years (range, 17 to 49 years).
The right ankle was involved in six cases.
All patients had a history of posterolateral ankle pain with pain on palpation over the peroneal tendons and a positive resistance test.
The average interval between the start of the symptoms and the diagnostic tendoscopy was 15 months (6 months to 3 years).
In two patients the strength of both peronei was slightly diminished.
In one patient a mobile ﬂat-foot deformity was present due to peroneal spasm.
Two patients presented with pain and swelling over the peroneal tendons after a bone-block transfer for recurrent peroneal tendon luxation.
One patient developed a peroneal tendinopathy after a posterolateral arthrotomy for a posterior ankle impingement syndrome.
The peroneal strength in this patient was slightly diminished.
Two patients had chronic symptoms over the peroneal tendons after operative ﬁxation of an ankle fracture.
The interval between the original operative procedures and tendoscopy was an average of 2.2 years (range, 1.4 to 3.0 years).
Three of these patients had an average of 7° decrease of dorsiﬂexion (5° to 10°).
In the other patients the range of motion was unrestricted.
Radiographs did not show degenerative changes.
One patient had a painful prominence over the lateral calcaneus between both peroneal tendons.
A mobile ﬂat-foot deformity was present due to peroneal spasm.
Standard radiographs did not reveal any pathol- resected in two cases.
A release of adhesions was performed in another case.
All were free of symptoms at an average of 24 months (range, 18 to 34 months).
In patients with recurrent dislocation of the peroneal tendons the patient complains of lateral instability, giving way, lateral pain, and, occasionally, a snapping sensation.16-18 The dislocation can be reproduced by active eversion of the slightly dorsiﬂected foot against resistance.
When the location cannot be reproduced, the cause of the snap often remains unclear.
Peroneal tendon disorders are often associated with chronic lateral ankle instability.
As the peroneal muscles act as lateral ankle stabilizers, more strain is placed on these tendons in chronic lateral instability resulting in hyper- trophic tendinopathy, tenosynovitis, and, ultimately, in (partial) tendon tears.7,19,20 Diagnosis may be difficult in a patient with lateral ankle pain.
Peroneal tendon dislocation and tenosynovitis can be detected by clinical examination.
In case of (subtotal) tears of the peroneus brevis or longus tendon, supplemental investigations might be helpful in establishing the diagnosis.19 Postsurgery or postfracture adhesions and irregulari- ties of the posterior aspect of the ﬁbula (tendon sliding channel) are a further cause for symptoms in this region.
Peroneal tendon disorders must be differenti- ated from (fatigue) fractures of the ﬁbula, lesions of the lateral ligament complex and posterolateral im- pingement syndrome (os trigonum).

RESULTS
The mean follow-up was 19 months (range, 14 to 24 months).
There were no complications.
Of the ﬁve patients who had a previous operative procedure, in four patients, adhesions between the tendons and tendon sheath were found and resected.
Three of these patients (in whom resection of adhesions took place) were free of symptoms at the last follow-up.
One patient remained symptomatic.
In one patient with a previous posterior ankle arthrotomy, the diagnostic tendoscopy did not reveal any pathology.
This patient remained symptomatic at the last follow-up.

RESULTS
The semiprofessional windsurfer had a longitudinal rupture in the peroneal brevis tendon (Figs 6-8).
The rupture was located at the tip of the lateral malleolus and had a length of approximately 4 cm.
Through a small incision a tendon repair was performed.
The patient was free of symptoms 6 weeks after operation.
Resumption of sports and full recovery of strength was present 12 weeks after operation.
He remained symptom free at 2-year follow-up with full work and sports activity.

RESULTS
One patient had a painful bony calcaneal prominence situated between the peroneal brevis and longus tendons some 4 to 5 cm distal from the tip of the ﬁbula.
Under tendoscopic control, this prominent peroneal tubercle was removed by burr.
The patient was symptom free 5 months after operation and remained symptom free at the last follow-up.
The peroneal spasm and relative ﬂat-foot deformity that was present before the operation disappeared.

The distal muscle ﬁbers of the peroneus brevis were resected.
In both cases, the snap remained present at the last follow-up.

477TENDOSCOPY could cause thickening and scarring with subsequent painful and limited dorsiﬂection of the ankle.8 We performed tendoscopy of the peroneal tendons as a diagnostic procedure.
All our patients did not respond to a long period (at least 6 months) of conservative treatment.
Patients in whom pathology such as adhesions, tendon rupture, or exostosis was found could be treated successfully by a tendoscopic procedure.
Future research in future patients will have to further determine the place of peroneal tendoscopy for indications like snapping tendon phenomena, deformity of the sliding channel, and symptomatic vincula.

RESULTS
DISCUSSION The balance between the peroneal tendons and the posterior tibial tendon plays an important role in the normal hind foot function.
Post-traumatic and postsur- gery complaints located at the posterior margin of the malleoli often pose a difficult diagnostic and therapeu- tic problem.
In the absence of intra-articular pathology, adhesions and irregularity of the tendon sliding chan- nel can give rise to symptomatic tendon pathology.8 Posttraumatic tendon dysfunction can lead to peritendi- nitis.
When conservative treatment fails, tenosynovec- tomy can be performed.
In our clinic, open tendon release and debridement require postoperative plaster immobilization and 4 to 5 days hospitalization.
The main reason for plaster immobilization is the preven- tion of equinus malformation.7,10 Plaster immobiliza- tion enhances the risk of subsequent new adhesion formation between tendons and tendon sheath.
Endoscopic release in combination with synovec- tomy has several advantages: out-patient procedure, diminished pain, and quick work and sports resump- tion.21 Other advantages of a diagnostic or therapeutic procedure tendoscopy include the fact that the proce- dure can be performed under local anesthesia and can be associated with functional aftertreatment.8 Local anesthesia is especially beniﬁcial in patients who present with a reproducable audible click located over the peroneal tendons.
Snapping phenomena around the ankle often remain unsolved.
When the snap can be reproduced by active movement of the foot, a diagnos- tic dynamic tendoscopy can be performed under local anaesthesia.
In the two patients with suspected pero- neal snap without a dislocation over the lateral malleo- lus, the peroneal tendons were found to snap over each other at the level of the tip of the lateral malleolus.
Endoscopic resection of the peroneal brevis vincula did not resolve the problem.
Tenodesis of the tendons (fusing both tendons to each other) has been proposed to both patients, but thus far has not been performed.

RESULTS
A new ﬁnding is the vincula that connects the peroneal tendon to their tendon sheath.
Several authors have detected vinculae within the tendon sheath of the ﬂexor tendon of the ﬁngers.22-26 Other locations include the ﬂexor tendon sheath of the toe ﬂexor at the level of the foot and the anterior tibial tendon.24,27 The peroneal vinculae only recently have been described to connect the peroneal tendons to their tendon sheath.28 The vinculae are described as a synovial lining reﬂected around the tendon or as special folds of connective tissue.22,24 They are supposed to play a role in the vascularity of the tendon.27-29 Nerve ﬁbers are found within the vincula.30 The vinculae that were consistently present in all our cadaver specimens as well as all our patients could become symptomatic in a post-traumatic situation.
